Descriptive Analysis of Static Data

Maria Gordillo-Maranon

2018-03-06

Key Points

New defined cohort of study as participants following Johnson et al (2017) exclusion criteria and removing patients: (i) who had been >1 times in ICU, (ii) who had >1 records of hospital admission, (iii) >89 years old. The new cohort included 36,227 patients.

Categorisation of BMI (bmi_cat), service of admission (service_cat) and ethnicity (race_cat).

The descriptive and independence analysis (Chi-squared test) between categorical static variables and mortality suggested that ethnicity (P< 2.2e-16), service of admission (P< 2.2e-16), BMI (P=2.662e-16), and gender (P=0.002) were associated with mortality.

Interestingly, the proportion of cardiac surgery patients who died in ICU was lower compared to other patients (1.9%), being neurological medical the higher percentage (13.5%). Hispanic showed to have a lower proportion of deaths in ICU, and patients with a BMI >25 are less likely to die.

Defining the cohort

In addition to Johnson et al (2017) exclusion criteria, we extended the exclusion criteria as follows:

  • Remove patients who had been >1 times in ICU.
  • Remove patients who had >1 records of hospital admission.
  • Remove patients >89 years old. Patients who are older than 89 years old at any time in the database have had their date of birth shifted to obscure their age and comply with HIPAA. The shift process was as follows: the patients age at their first admission was determined. The date of birth was then set to exactly 300 years before their first admission.
JohnsonCohort <- subset(Cohort, 
                 subset = (exclusion_over_15 == 0) &
                   (exclusion_valid_data == 0) & 
                   (exclusion_stay_lt_4hr == 0) &
                   (exclusion_organ_donor == 0))

dim(JohnsonCohort)

# Select the ones that are not duplicated

NewCohort <- JohnsonCohort[(!duplicated(JohnsonCohort$subject_id) & age<89),c("subject_id","hadm_id","icustay_id","intime", "outtime", "age","gender", "ethnicity", "icu_los", "hosp_los","death_icu") ]

# Number of patients >89 (removed) 
nrow(JohnsonCohort[(!duplicated(JohnsonCohort$subject_id) & age>89)])

dim(NewCohort)

After applying the additional criteria, the cohort reduces from 52085 patients to 36227 (1960 were >89 yo). The new dataset contains information for 11 variables instead of 61: subject_id, hadm_id, icustay_id, intime, outtime, age, gender, ethnicity, icu_los, hosp_los, death_icu.

The static data is merged with the general information using the icustay_id. This process results in a 36198 patients with 41 associated variables.

NewCohort_static<- merge(NewCohort, Dfstatic, by = "icustay_id") 
dim(NewCohort_static)
names(NewCohort_static)

It can be seen that 29 patients did not have static data. These are stored in MissingStaticsDF.

nrow(NewCohort_static[subject_id.x==subject_id.y])
nrow(NewCohort_static[hadm_id.x==hadm_id.y])

# Number of patients in the full data (NewCohort) who did not have static data
length(unique(NewCohort_static$icustay_id))
length(unique(NewCohort$icustay_id))

# Which ones have been missed in the analysis
missing_statics <- setdiff(sort(unique(NewCohort$icustay_id)), sort(unique(NewCohort_static$icustay_id)))

MissingStaticsDF = list()
for(ele in missing_statics){
  MissingStaticsDF <- rbind(MissingStaticsDF, NewCohort[icustay_id==ele])
}

Preliminary analysis

To evaluate the independance between the static variables and mortality, Pearsons chi-squared test was used. The chi-squared test is used to determine whether there is a significant difference between the expected frequencies and the observed frequencies in one or more categories. This test of independence assesses whether unpaired observations on two variables, expressed in a contingency table, are independent of each other.

  • Ethnicity vs mortality. Test the hypothesis whether the ethnicity is independent of mortality at 0.05 significance level. As the p-value is < 2.2e-16, there was enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that ethnicity was independent of mortality. In other words, the chi-squared result gave reasonable evidence to suggest an association between ethnicity and mortality.
# Table function to tally ethnicity and mortality 
tb1 <- table(NewCohort_static$race_cat, NewCohort_static$death_icu)
chisq.test(tb1)
  • BMI vs Mortality. As the p-value of the Chi-squared test is = 2.662e-16, there was enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that BMI category was independent of mortality.
tb2 <- table(NewCohort_static$bmi_cat, NewCohort_static$death_icu)
chisq.test(tb2)
  • Gender vs Mortality. As the p-value of the Chi-squared test is = 0.002, there was enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that gender was independent of mortality. Note that the Yatess correction for continuity was done since the values of mortality in both females and males are below 5%. To reduce the error in approximation, Frank Yates, an English statistician, suggested a correction for continuity that adjusts the formula for Pearsons chi-squared test by subtracting 0.5 from the difference between each observed value and its expected value in a 2 2 contingency table. This reduces the chi-squared value obtained and thus increases its p-value.
tb3 <- table(NewCohort_static$gender, NewCohort_static$death_icu)
chisq.test(tb3)
  • Service vs Mortality. As the p-value is < 2.2e-16, there was strong evidence to suggest an association between the service of admission and mortality.
tb4 <- table(NewCohort_static$service_cat, NewCohort_static$death_icu)
chisq.test(tb4)
